    Update Deployment to Use Helm Templates

    Update Deployment to Use Helm Templates
    Need help? Contact our support team

    Introduction

    In this Lab Step, you'll learn how to use the helm and kubectl commands together to deploy a provided Helm Chart into the Kubernetes cluster. In this scenario the provided app Helm Chart has been configured to create a Deployment which launches a single pod containing two containers. The first container is a NGINX web server container which proxies incoming HTTP requests downstream to a second container running a FLASK based web application - based on the Docker image you built in the first Lab Step. You'll learn how to use a Helm Values file to externalize runtime variables, ensuring that your Helm templates can be reused across different environments, for example say dev and prod environments.

    Notes:

    • Helm 2.0 is used
    • The Helm Tiller cluster side service is NOT used

    Instructions

    1. For starters lets reset the cluster back to an almost empty state. Use the kubectl delete command to delete the Deployment, Pod, and Service resources created earlier. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl delete deploy,pods,svc --all

    2. Within the Explorer view, navigate to and open the Helm lab/code/App/lab-code/app/values.yaml file.

    Take sometime to review and understand the design and intent of the Helm values.yaml file. This file contains the values that are injected into their respective placeholders located within the templates/*.yaml files when the helm template command is executed.

    3. Within the values.yaml file locate and edit the #Code3.0 comment block, adding the following configuration:

    #CODE3.0:
    #create new configuration value which will store a message to be passed into the Flask web app as an environment variable
    webapp:
      message: CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm

    This is used to declare the variable webapp.message which holds the string "CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm". The variable webapp.message is referenced within the templates/deployment.yaml file which you will edit and update next.

    Notes:

    • Make sure that you save (CTRL+S) the updated values.yaml file BEFORE proceeding onto the next step - this is very important!!
    • Make sure that the indentation is maintained
    • Consider copying the content directly from the provided version found in the equivalent solution-code directory: lab/code/App/solution-code/app/values.yaml

    Your updated values.yaml file should look like this:

    4. Within the Explorer view, navigate to and open the Helm lab/code/App/lab-code/app/templates/deployment.yaml file. 

    5. Within the deployment.yaml file locate and edit the #Code3.1 comment block, adding the following configuration:

    #CODE3.1:
    #create the APP_NAME environment variable and configure to use the Helm value {{ .Values.webapp.message }}
    - name: APP_NAME
      value: {{ .Values.webapp.message }}

    This is used to reference the variable webapp.message which holds the string "CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm".

    Notes:

    • Make sure that you save (CTRL+S) the updated deployment.yaml file BEFORE proceeding onto the next step - this is very important!!
    • Make sure that the indentation is maintained
    • Consider copying the content directly from the provided version found in the equivalent solution-code directory: lab/code/App/solution-code/app/templates/deployment.yaml

    Your updated deployment.yaml file should look like this: 

    6. Use the helm template command to generate a deployable manifest file. In the terminal execute the following command:

    helm template ./app

    Examine the output of the previous command and confirm that the {{ .Values.webapp.message }} placeholder within the Deployment resource has indeed been replaced with the respective value "CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm" as seen above.

    Notes:

    • The previous command ONLY generated the deployable manifest - it hasn't yet been deployed into the cluster. This is useful to validate the resulting manifest BEFORE actually deploying it.

    7. This time you will perform the actual deployment into the cluster. To do so you will again use the helm template command to generate a deployable manifest file, piping the output (manifest) directly into the kubectl apply command. In the terminal execute the following command:

    helm template --name cloudacademy ./app | kubectl apply -f -

    Confirm that the declared templated resources within the ./app Helm project have been created successfully as seen above.

    8. Examine the current services available within the cluster . In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl get svc

     
    Notice the newly created cloudacademy-app service - and its assigned cluster IP address.

    9. Extract the cloudacademy-app service cluster IP address and store it in a variable named CLOUDACADEMY_APP_IP. Echo it back out to the terminal. In the terminal execute the following commands:

    CLOUDACADEMY_APP_IP=`kubectl get service/cloudacademy-app -o jsonpath='{.spec.clusterIP}'`
    echo $CLOUDACADEMY_APP_IP

    10. Test the cloudacademy-app service by sending a curl request to it. In the terminal execute the following command:

    curl -i http://$CLOUDACADEMY_APP_IP

    Confirm that the body of the HTTP response contains the string "Hello World - CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm". Again this demonstrates how to leverage environment variables at runtime. Recall that the APP_NAME environment variable as declared within the deployment.yaml Helm template file has the value "CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm" injected into it by the helm template command. The resulting string is then used at runtime within the FLASK web application container, and is returned within the body of the HTTP response when requested - as just observed. 

    11. Moving on. Create both dev and prod specific copies of the app/values.yaml file. In the terminal execute the following command:

    cp app/values.yaml app/values.dev.yaml
    cp app/values.yaml app/values.prod.yaml

    12. Within the Explorer view, navigate to and open the Helm lab/code/App/lab-code/app/values.dev.yaml file. Update the webapp.message variable to have the expanded string "CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm.Dev", like so:

    Notes:

    • Make sure that you save (CTRL+S) the updated values.dev.yaml file BEFORE proceeding onto the next step - this is very important!!
    • Make sure that the indentation is maintained 

    13. Perform a dev redeployment back into the cluster by referencing the values.dev.yaml Values file within the helm template command. In the terminal execute the following command:

    helm template --name cloudacademy -f ./app/values.dev.yaml ./app | kubectl apply -f -

    14. Retest the cloudacademy-app service by sending another curl request to it. In the terminal execute the following command:

    curl -i http://$CLOUDACADEMY_APP_IP

    Confirm that the body of the HTTP response contains the string "Hello World - CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm.Dev". This value was the updated string you edited and saved within the lab/code/App/lab-code/app/values.dev.yaml file. 

    15. Within the Explorer view, navigate to and open the Helm lab/code/App/lab-code/app/values.prod.yaml file. Update the webapp.message variable to have the expanded string "CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm.Prod", like so:

    Notes:

    • Make sure that you save (CTRL+S) the updated values.prod.yaml file BEFORE proceeding onto the next step - this is very important!!
    • Make sure that the indentation is maintained  

    16. Perform a prod redeployment back into the cluster by referencing the values.prod.yaml Values file within the helm template command. In the terminal execute the following command:

    helm template --name cloudacademy -f ./app/values.prod.yaml ./app | kubectl apply -f -

    17. Retest the cloudacademy-app service by sending another curl request to it. In the terminal execute the following command:

    curl -i http://$CLOUDACADEMY_APP_IP 

    Confirm that the body of the HTTP response contains the string "Hello World - CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm.Prod". This value was the updated string you edited and saved within the lab/code/App/lab-code/app/values.prod.yaml file. 

      

    Summary

    In this Lab Step, you'll learnt how to use the helm and kubectl commands together to deploy a provided Helm Chart into the Kubernetes cluster. The deployment consisted of a single pod containing two containers. The first container was a NGINX web server container which proxied incoming HTTP requests downstream to a second container running a FLASK based web application - based on the Docker image you built in the first Lab Step. You then learnt how to use a Helm Values file to externalize runtime variables, ensuring that your Helm templates are resuable across different environments, in this case dev and prod environments, via the values.dev.yaml and values.prod.yaml files respectively. 

    Validation checks
    2Checks
    Check Deployment Exists

    Check the cloudacademy-app deployment now exists with 1 running replica

    Check the Correct Web Response is Returned

    Check that the body of the HTTP response contains the substring "Hello World - CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Helm"
